Who you are. 
Who you’ve been. 
Who you will be. 

Definitely remembering again. 

#purpose

It’s particularly egregious coming from those who are leaders in the Church. 

Last time that I checked (in my best Nipsey voice), a little tussle with the Lord and questions about our faith go back centuries. It won’t take much time in the Passages to find truth in that statement. 

Cheers to the ones who’ve chosen to sit with, listen and hear the hearts of those who are holding one of the most beautiful parts of our tradition. 

I wonder if one of the reasons these curiosities are so weaponized is because they have too often made appearances in the minds of those and have been swatted away like an annoying fly for fear of what may happen to status quo. (Money, power, nepotism, status, saviorism…and the list goes on.) 

My question to those who may have this experience is, “What will happen if you don’t shoo them away?” What will happen if you choose to sit with the hard feelings and the questions? What will happen if you settle in past the fear? What kind of movement will happen when you remove the weight of defending the Church and upholding the status quo? 

I’ve had a ‘complicated’ relationship with the ‘little c’ (as opposed to the Big G) for a little while now and I guess it’s imperative for those who like to tussle with the wrong part of an argument to make the distinction between that (little c) and the reason ‘that’ even exists. 

Maybe I’m a little “internet late” for this topic but I know too many in my own circle who quietly wrestle (which is fine) for fear of being misunderstood by those they were once in close “community” with. See the irony here? 

I just keep sayin-regardless of what anyone may say or think or how they may judge the decisions and moves of those they do not understand-God’s never confused by it. I think it will be helpful for many of us to remember this then, if you ‘are’ someone bothered by these decisions/the way people have chosen to move, ask yourself why. I think why’s always a good place to start with most things. 
.
.
.

This part of the year tends to inherently call for a lot of reflection. 

The season of life I’m in, even more…

One thing I can agree with myself on (this just means I’ve found resolution and peace with this truth) is that my peace and joy are more a non-negotiable than ever. 

This is a truth that I will proclaim and practice even more as I move into 2024. 

I’m not one for resolutions. 

I tend to follow the ebbs and flows and rhythms of life-following my gut and intuition where it leads me. It has yet to steer me wrong. 

This next year, I’m leaning more into moments that produce the one you see here - to give back to the girl you see in the second image. She deserves every ounce of goodness and joy and richness this side of heaven has. 

In case you forgot-you do, too. 

p.s. that side pony tho

Consistency. 
And, a love letter to the week (and year) ahead.

The next to last video pretty much sums up the goal. 😉

SWIPE <<<👈🏾 to see what I mean.

Just made FORTY FIVE revolutions. Time is a funny thing. 👇🏾

I am learning how to get past the idea that some of my most recent years feel a bit like they were stolen from me. 

I need to know this truth so that I can move into a space that helps me see that each moment is a gift and things that are stolen can indeed be retrieved. Redeemed, in a way. I want to live this truth so that I can be free. 

The gap between the needing and the wanting is a chasm as wide as the soul and still-I long to discover its depths. I think this is where gratitude flourishes. Where it peeks through the crevices of pain like the first break of morning sun. It leaks and spills through the cracks and touches anything dead or alive. Yeah, I think gratitude’s something like the sun. 

This is not an easy path but, it is one that I trepidatiously yet humbly choose with each day that I am gifted another opportunity to breathe. 

Admittedly, as I enter this year, I feel as blind as ever. It’s not really the most comfortable thing to admit, is it? To not know the thing that most seem to know this time of year. At this age…

I search for parts of myself in places I’ve long abandoned. Like an explorer in a dark cavern, I await the light to guide me.

Even more, I am discovering I am the light. 

I hope you are discovering more of your light, too. 
I hope you are discovering more of your light, too. 
I hope you are discovering more of your light, too.

Grow. 

I’m a bit obsessed with my houseplants.
That’s not necessarily unique to me-most people who have houseplants are. 

Recently, however, I’ve taken particular interest in watching each leaf break free from its shell to form into a matured leaf. 

In order to reveal its true ‘self’, it must break free from the outer layer that provided shelter, nurture and protection. 

I’m not a leaf and neither are you, of course, but there is great parallel in this botanical process for us as human beings. 

Like the leaf, our human growth requires some breaking out and through to become what we are meant to be. 

But, what has to happen in order for each of us to truly grow? 

Some shedding of hold habits, relationships, breaking away of unhealthy thought patterns and ways of being that may have once served us but no longer do. 

How do we embrace this type of growth? 

I have more questions than answers currently but I can feel the breaking. 

Still no resolutions here, but I’m leaning into what it looks like to embrace (new) growth this year. How about you?

P.S. I stumbled on that picture of HS me at the end and it sparked all kinds of emotions. More about that in a few weeks as I continue to process.
